          "body": "The psalm does not end with the assurance of verse 6; it opens into an optative prayer that carries the whole argument beyond its immediate pastoral moment. Verse 7's *mi yitten* — 'oh, that' or 'who will give?' — is the Psalter's idiom for intense longing, used when no present answer is visible and only a divine gift will do. The psalmist prays that 'the salvation (*yeshuah*) of Israel would come out of Zion.' The word *yeshuah* — deliverance, rescue — is the same root as the name Yeshua (Jesus). The New Testament writers are not making an etymological trick when they identify Jesus as Israel's *yeshuah*; they are reading the Psalter's own vocabulary as fulfilled in His person and work. Paul quotes Psalm 14 in Romans 3 to establish universal condemnation, then closes Romans 11 with the declaration that 'all Israel will be saved' and grounds it in Isaiah 59:20-21 — 'the Deliverer will come from Zion.' The psalm's final verse is not an appendix; it is the psalm's resolution. Against the darkness of 'not even one does good,' the only hope is a salvation that comes from outside the human situation entirely — from Zion, initiated by YHWH, received by the covenant community that will then rejoice under both its names, Jacob and Israel."
